, 0.020113801583647728, 0.019519038498401642, 0.005623213015496731, -0.02811606600880623, 0.032246965914964676, 0.005926001351326704, -0.006201755255460739, -0.012836065143346786, -0.014036404900252819, 0.034799039363861084, 0.0007366950158029795, -0.022449597716331482, 0.03572903200984001, 0.021476348862051964, -0.008661910891532898, 0.04213084280490875, 0.017615796998143196, -0.023184940218925476, 0.02772676572203636, 0.01334431767463684, -0.019043227657675743, 0.023206567391753197, 0.01938927173614502, 0.033133700489997864, 0.03601019084453583, -0.01279280986636877, 0.011614098213613033, 0.013333503156900406, 0.04245525971055031, -0.003695640480145812, 0.002527742413803935, -0.0020573390647768974, 0.059216760098934174]], "input": ["\"CONSTANT SALES MIX PV CHART\":\"Assuming a constant mix of products based on the budgeted sales, it is only necessary to know the profit for two values of sales (to plot on the graph and draw a straight line between them): The most straightforward point is where revenue = 0 (i.e. where the company makes a loss equal to fixed costs). For the second point it makes most sense to calculate profit for total budgeted sales.\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF MULTI-PRODUCT PROFIT-VOLUME CHART\":\"Zed Co makes two products, Exe and Wye. Details of these two products are as follows: Selling price ($/unit) Exe: 40, Wye: 60; Contribution ($/unit) Exe: 24, Wye: 18; Budgeted sales (units) Exe: 10,000, Wye: 10,000. Total fixed costs are budgeted at $100,000. When sales revenue = 0, loss = $100,000 (fixed costs). At total budgeted sales: Revenue = (10,000 * 40) + (10,000 * 60) = $1,000,000. Profit = Contribution - Fixed cost = (10,000 * 24) + (10,000 * 18) - 100,000 = 320,000.\"", "\"SALES BY PROFITABILITY PV CHART\":\"An alternative assumption is that sales are not made in a standard sales mix but by prioritizing the most profitable products (i.e. the company produces and sells the product with the highest contribution first). Products are, therefore, ranked according to their C/S ratios. In this case, the PV chart will no longer be a straight line; it will be 'kinked'.\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF SALES BY PROFITABILITY\":\"Assuming now that Zed Co decides to produce and sell the product that has the highest C/S ratio up to the maximum budgeted (10,000 units), followed by the other product (again up to maximum 10,000 units). Selling price ($/unit) Exe: 40, Wye: 60; Contribution ($/unit) Exe: 24, Wye: 18; C/S ratio Exe: 0.6, Wye: 0.3; Ranking Exe: 1st, Wye: 2nd. The cumulative profit/(loss) corresponding to cumulative revenue is calculated as follows: Sales volume Exe 10,000: Contribution 240,000, Cumulative profit/loss 140,000, Revenue 400,000, Cumulative revenue 400,000; Sales volume Wye 10,000: Contribution 180,000, Cumulative profit/loss 320,000, Revenue 600,000, Cumulative revenue 1,000,000.\"", "\"FIXED COST\":\"Fixed cost\" refers to business expenses that are not dependent on the level of goods or services produced by the business. These costs do not change with the level of production or sales volume and remain constant regardless of the business's output. Examples of fixed costs include rent, salaries, and insurance.", "\"SALES MIX PERCENTAGE\":\"Sales mix percentage = Sales of a particular product / Total sales\"", "\"BUDGETED SALES\":\"Budgeted sales\" are the estimated sales volume or revenue that a company expects to achieve in a future period. This projection represents the anticipated amount of sales revenue for a specified timeframe, providing a financial target for the company to aim for.", "\"TOTAL BUDGETED REVENUE\":\"Total budgeted revenue = Sum of budgeted revenue for all products\"", "\"C/S RATIO\":The \"C/S RATIO\" is defined as the ratio of the contribution per unit to the selling price per unit. For products C, S, and D, the C/S ratios are 0.55, 0.35, and 0.23 respectively.", "\"BREAKEVEN REVENUE\":\"Breakeven revenue = Fixed cost / C/S ratio\"", "\"MULTI-PRODUCT BREAKEVEN CHARTS\":\"This quiz involves constructing a PV chart for two products, 'boy racer' and 'family saloon,' based on budgeted sales and different sales assumptions.\"", "\"MULTI-PRODUCT SITUATIONS\":\"In multi-product situations, a fixed product mix is necessary to work with. If the product mix varies, there could be many breakeven points. Multi-product PV charts help in visualizing the relationship between revenue and profit.\"", "\"SUMMARY OF CVP ANALYSIS\":\"The summary of CVP analysis includes the breakeven point, breakeven chart, profit-volume chart, and the limitations due to simplifying assumptions.\"", "\"CONTRIBUTION PER UNIT\":\"Contribution per unit\" is calculated as the selling price per unit minus the variable cost per unit. It represents the amount each unit contributes to covering fixed costs and generating profit. The variable cost per unit includes materials cost, direct labor, and variable overhead.", "\"VARIABLE COST PER UNIT\":\"Variable cost per unit\" is the cost that varies with the level of output. It is calculated by summing the per-unit costs of materials, labor, and variable overheads. In this case, it is $21 per unit. Additionally, \"variable cost per unit\" is represented by the gradient of the total cost line, which is also constant.", "\"SELLING PRICE PER UNIT\":The \"SELLING PRICE PER UNIT\" is the amount a customer pays for a single unit of a product or service. For products C, S, and D, the selling prices per unit are $110, $160, and $120 respectively. The selling price per unit remains constant, as indicated by the straight line of total revenue."], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}